{"title_page": "Sigvard Bernadotte", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| image = LRK-SigvardB.jpg\n| name = Sigvard Bernadotte\n| full name = Sigvard Oscar Fredrik Bernadotte\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1907|6|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Stockholm Palace]], [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2002|2|4|1907|6|7|df=y}}\n| death_place = Stockholm, Sweden\n| burial_date = 15 February 2002\n| burial_place =[[Kungliga begravningsplatsen|Royal Cemetery]], [[Solna Municipality|Solna]], Sweden\n| title =  Count of Wisborg<br>prev. Duke of Uppland\n| father = [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden]]\n| mother = [[Princess Margaret of Connaught]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Erica Maria Patzek|1934|1943|reason=div}} <br> {{marriage|Sonja Christensen Robbert|1943|1961|reason=div}} <br>{{marriage|[[Marianne Lindberg]]<br>|1961}}\n| issue = Count Michael Sigvard Bernadotte af Wisborg\n| house = [[House of Bernadotte|Bernadotte]]\n}}\n\n'''Sigvard Oscar Fredrik Bernadotte''', [[Prince Bernadotte]], [[Count of Wisborg]] (7 June 1907 &ndash; 4 February 2002), was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] prince and [[industrial designer]].\n\nHe was the second son of [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden|King Gustav VI Adolf]] of Sweden and his first wife, [[Princess Margaret of Connaught]], a granddaughter of Britain's [[Queen Victoria]]. He was born a Swedish prince and was originally titled Duke of Uppland, but was excluded from the line of succession and lost his Swedish titles <ref>Prof. Gunnar Bramst\u00e5ng in ''''Tronr\u00e4tt, b\u00f6rdstitel och hustillh\u00f6righet'' {{ISBN|91-544-2081-4}} p. 54 ff</ref> in 1934 when he married a commoner. He was a paternal uncle of [[King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] and a maternal uncle of Queen [[Margrethe II of Denmark]] and [[Queen Anne-Marie of Greece]].\n\n==Professional life==\nAn industrial designer, Bernadotte was known for designing everything from luxurious silver objects for [[Georg Jensen]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040623145007/http://www.hollsten.com/news/sigvard.htm ]</ref> to everyday-use household items in plastic.\n\nAmong his iconic designs were the Red Clara opener; EKA Swede 38 folding knife;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents/USD227071 |title=Patent USD227071 - Winifred e - Google Patents |publisher=Google.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-02}}</ref> the Margrethe bowl; the Bernadotte jug, and the Facit Private typewriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sassabrassa.se/?page_id=44 |title=sassabrassa \u00bb Sigvard Bernadotte |publisher=Sassabrassa.se |date=2013-06-16 |accessdate=2014-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203203537/http://www.sassabrassa.se/?page_id=44 |archivedate=2012-12-03 }}</ref> He also designed glasses frames.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://svenskdam.se/2010/01/sigvard-bernadotte-%E2%80%93-det-kungliga-arets-hetaste-glasogondesigner/ |title=Sigvard Bernadotte \u2013 det kungliga \u00e5rets hetaste glas\u00f6gondesigner! &#124; Svensk Damtidning |publisher=Svenskdam.se |date= |accessdate=2014-03-02}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as an [[assistant director]] at [[MGM]] in [[Culver City, California]] and served as a technical advisor on the 1937 film ''[[The Prisoner of Zenda (1937 film)|The Prisoner of Zenda]]''.\n\nHe appeared briefly in the 1968 Italian mondo film Sweden: Heaven and Hell. His work in industrial design at Bernadotte Design AB is featured, along with select items from his portfolio.\n\n==Marriages==\nHe married Erika Maria Regina Rosalie Patzek (1911\u20132007) on 8 March 1934. She was the daughter of German businessman Anton Patzek and his wife Maria Anna Lala. The wedding took place in [[Caxton Hall]] in London and the witnesses were the bride's brother Georg Patzek and a lawyer Mr Gordon. Sigvard lost all royal privileges following the wedding and started his silver design business. They were divorced on 14 October 1943. \n\nBernadotte remarried a Danish woman Sonia Robbert (1909\u20132004) on 26 October 1943 and they were divorced on 6 June 1961. They had one son: Michael (b. 21 August 1944) who married Christine Wellhofer on 6 February 1976, and they in turn have one daughter and one granddaughter.\n\nLastly, Bernadotte married Swedish actress [[Marianne Bernadotte|Marianne Lindberg Tchang]] on 30 July 1961.\n\n==Title==\nBernadotte was born Prince of Sweden and Duke of Uppland, but having made an [[Royal intermarriage#Morganatic marriage|unequal match]] was disqualified from the [[Line of succession to the Swedish throne|line of succession]]. He was also forbidden to use his birth titles<ref>[[Gunnar Bramst\u00e5ng]] in ''''Tronr\u00e4tt, b\u00f6rdstitel och hustillh\u00f6righet'' {{ISBN|91-544-2081-4}} p. 54-55</ref> and left to be called ''Mr. Bernadotte''. His cousin [[Lennart Bernadotte]], who two years earlier had experienced the same thing (as the first Swede in history), considered himself, and even more so Sigvard, subjected to very cruel treatment for several decades by the [[Royal Court of Sweden]] due to their marriages.<ref>[[Lennart Bernadotte]] in ''Mainau min medelpunkt'' {{ISBN|91-0-056122-3}} p. 77</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 1951, for himself, his wife and his marital descendants, Bernadotte was admitted by [[Grand Duchess Charlotte of Luxembourg|Grand Duchess Charlotte]] ([[head of state]] at the time) into the nobility of Luxembourg with the title [[Count of Wisborg]].<ref name=\"OAF\">{{cite book|editor1-last=von Rothstein|editor1-first=Niclas|title=Kalender \u00f6ver Ointroducerad adels f\u00f6rening|date=2009|publisher=[[Ointroducerad Adels F\u00f6rening]]|isbn=9789163350382|page=22|edition=22nd|language=Swedish}}</ref> and in that conferral was also called ''Sigvard Oscar Frederik Prince Bernadotte''.<ref>''[[M\u00e9morial]] du Grand-Duch\u00e9 de Luxembourg [http://data.legilux.public.lu/file/eli-etat-leg-memorial-1951-48-fr-pdf.pdf]'', Government of Luxembourg, 13 August 1951, entry dated 18 July 1951, p. 1135</ref> \n\nAfter more than 30 years of argument and controversy in Sweden over his rank and titles, problems which worsened when his father died in 1973, and fed up after having been demonstratively snubbed by the Royal Court of Sweden during a state visit by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] in 1983, Bernadotte announced to [[Tidningarnas Telegrambyr\u00e5]] on 28 May of that year that he was to be known as ''Prince Sigvard Bernadotte'' from then on.<ref>[[Marianne Bernadotte]] in ''Glimtar och scener'' [[Norstedts]] Stockholm 1986 {{ISBN|91-1-863442-7}} pp. 161 & 175-179: entire paragraph</ref>\n\nOver the years since then, based on precedent established in 1888 for his great-uncle [[Prince Oscar Bernadotte|Oscar]],<ref>[https://www.svd.se/lang-kamp-for-prinstitel-forgaves Article] by Anita Bergmark in ''[[Svenska Dagbladet]]'' 2002-05-02</ref> and citing Oscar's title of nobility as it was confirmed by the Government of Luxembourg in 1892, Bernadotte was supported by several legal experts<ref>[http://wwwc.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/0105/14/kung.html Article] by Petter Ovander in ''[[Aftonbladet]]'' 2001-05-14 quoting three attorneys</ref> when he petitioned for acknowledgement in Sweden of the ''[[Prince Bernadotte]]'' title as his also,<ref>Roger Lundgren in ''[[Princess Sibylla of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Sibylla]], en biografi'' [[Bonniers]] {{ISBN|9789100111120}} p. 108, specifically naming that title as what Sigvard wanted acknowledged</ref> although he did not seek reinstatement in the line of succession to the throne as a royal prince of that country. [[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden|King Carl XVI Gustaf]] has been criticized for never obliging and for his consequent estrangement from his uncle.<ref>[https://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/ Article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810205908/https://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/ |date=2017-08-10 }} by Scott Ritcher in ''[[The Local]]'' 2009-12-23</ref>\n\nBernadotte went to the [[European Court of Human Rights]] in an effort to have the Government of Sweden acknowledge his princely title there, but in 2004, after his death, the ECHR declared the application inadmissible.<ref>[http://cmiskp.echr.coe.int/tkp197/view.asp?item=1&action=html&sessionid=94512204 ]{{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe wording on his gravestone, at the [[Kungliga begravningsplatsen|Royal Cemetery]], which is owned by the king, does make it clear that he was \"born Prince of Sweden\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Sigvard Bernadotte|url=http://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/|accessdate=2 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202215105/http://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/|archivedate=2 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1994 to 2002, he was the oldest living great-grandchild of [[Queen Victoria|Queen Victoria of the United Kingdom]], and having reached the age of 94, he was her longest-lived male descendant until being overtaken by his younger brother [[Count Carl Johan Bernadotte of Wisborg|Carl Johan]] on 29 June 2011.\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nBlason du Prince Sigvard duc d'Uppland.svg|Sigvard's arms as Prince of Sweden and Duke of Uppland\nArms of Prince Bernadotte 1951 Luxembourg.jpg|Arms as described by the Government of Luxembourg for [[Prince Bernadotte|Princes and Princesses Bernadotte]] in 1951\nArmoiries de Lennart Bernadotte comte de Wisborg.svg|Arms of the [[Count of Wisborg|Counts of Wisborg]]<ref name=\"OAF\"/>\n</gallery>\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Sigvard Bernadotte, Count of Wisborg'''\n|2= 2. [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Margaret of Connaught]]\n|4= 4. [[Gustaf V of Sweden]]\n|5= 5. [[Victoria of Baden|Princess Victoria of Baden]]\n|6= 6. [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn]]\n|7= 7. [[Princess Louise Margaret of Prussia]]\n|8= 8. [[Oscar II of Sweden]]\n|9= 9. [[Sophia of Nassau|Princess Sophia of Nassau]]\n|10= 10. [[Frederick I, Grand Duke of Baden]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Louise of Prussia]]\n|12= 12. [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n|13= 13. [[Queen Victoria|Victoria, Queen of the United Kingdom]]\n|14= 14. [[Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia (1828\u201385)|Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia]]\n|15= 15. [[Princess Maria Anna of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Swedish Act of Succession]]\n* [[Instrument of Government (1809)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0076027|name=Sigvard Bernadotte}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Bernadotte]]|7 June|1907|4 February|2002}}\n{{S-roy|se}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Uppland|Duke of Uppland]] | before=[[Prince Gustaf, Duke of Uppland|Prince Gustaf]] | after=none | years=}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{House of Bernadotte}}\n{{Swedish princes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernadotte, Sigvard}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Uppland|Uppland]]\n[[Category:Swedish memoirists]]\n[[Category:Swedish princes|Sigvard 1907]]\n[[Category:Swedish industrial designers]]\n[[Category:Uppsala University alumni]]\n[[Category:House of Bernadotte|Sigvard]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at Kungliga begravningsplatsen|Sigvard]]\n[[Category:Disinherited European royalty]]\n[[Category:Counts of Wisborg|Sigvard]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Prince Eugen Medal]]\n[[Category:Princes Bernadotte|Sigvard]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| image = LRK-SigvardB.jpg\n| name = Sigvard Bernadotte\n| full name = Sigvard Oscar Fredrik Bernadotte\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1907|6|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Stockholm Palace]], [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2002|2|4|1907|6|7|df=y}}\n| death_place = Stockholm, Sweden\n| burial_date = 15 February 2002\n| burial_place =[[Kungliga begravningsplatsen|Royal Cemetery]], [[Solna Municipality|Solna]], Sweden\n| title =  Count of Wisborg<br>prev. Duke of Uppland\n| father = [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden]]\n| mother = [[Princess Margaret of Connaught]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Erica Maria Patzek|1934|1943|reason=div}} <br> {{marriage|Sonja Christensen Robbert|1943|1961|reason=div}} <br>{{marriage|[[Marianne Lindberg]]<br>|1961}}\n| issue = Count Michael Sigvard Bernadotte af Wisborg\n| house = [[House of Bernadotte|Bernadotte]]\n}}\n\n'''Sigvard Oscar Fredrik Bernadotte''', [[Prince Bernadotte]], [[Count of Wisborg]] (7 June 1907 &ndash; 4 February 2002), was a [[Sweden|Swedish]] prince and [[industrial designer]].\n\nHe was the second son of [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden|King Gustav VI Adolf]] of Sweden and his first wife, [[Princess Margaret of Connaught]], a granddaughter of Britain's [[Queen Victoria]]. He was born a Swedish prince and was originally titled Duke of Uppland, but was excluded from the line of succession and lost his Swedish titles <ref>Prof. Gunnar Bramst\u00e5ng in ''''Tronr\u00e4tt, b\u00f6rdstitel och hustillh\u00f6righet'' {{ISBN|91-544-2081-4}} p. 54 ff</ref> in 1934 when he married a commoner. He was a paternal uncle of [[King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden]] and a maternal uncle of [[Queen Margrethe II of Denmark]] and [[Queen Anne-Marie of Greece]].\n\n==Professional life==\nAn industrial designer, Bernadotte was known for designing everything from luxurious silver objects for [[Georg Jensen]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040623145007/http://www.hollsten.com/news/sigvard.htm ]</ref> to everyday-use household items in plastic.\n\nAmong his iconic designs were the Red Clara opener; EKA Swede 38 folding knife;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents/USD227071 |title=Patent USD227071 - Winifred e - Google Patents |publisher=Google.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-02}}</ref> the Margrethe bowl; the Bernadotte jug, and the Facit Private typewriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sassabrassa.se/?page_id=44 |title=sassabrassa \u00bb Sigvard Bernadotte |publisher=Sassabrassa.se |date=2013-06-16 |accessdate=2014-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203203537/http://www.sassabrassa.se/?page_id=44 |archivedate=2012-12-03 }}</ref> He also designed glasses frames.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://svenskdam.se/2010/01/sigvard-bernadotte-%E2%80%93-det-kungliga-arets-hetaste-glasogondesigner/ |title=Sigvard Bernadotte \u2013 det kungliga \u00e5rets hetaste glas\u00f6gondesigner! &#124; Svensk Damtidning |publisher=Svenskdam.se |date= |accessdate=2014-03-02}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as an [[assistant director]] at [[MGM]] in [[Culver City, California]] and served as a technical advisor on the 1937 film ''[[The Prisoner of Zenda (1937 film)|The Prisoner of Zenda]]''.\n\nHe appeared briefly in the 1968 Italian mondo film Sweden: Heaven and Hell. His work in industrial design at Bernadotte Design AB is featured, along with select items from his portfolio.\n\n==Marriages==\nHe married Erika Maria Regina Rosalie Patzek (1911\u20132007) on 8 March 1934. She was the daughter of German businessman Anton Patzek and his wife Maria Anna Lala. The wedding took place in [[Caxton Hall]] in London and the witnesses were the bride's brother Georg Patzek and a lawyer Mr Gordon. Sigvard lost all royal privileges following the wedding and started his silver design business. They were divorced on 14 October 1943. \n\nBernadotte remarried a Danish woman Sonia Robbert (1909\u20132004) on 26 October 1943 and they were divorced on 6 June 1961. They had one son: Michael (b. 21 August 1944) who married Christine Wellhofer on 6 February 1976, and they in turn have one daughter and one granddaughter.\n\nLastly, Bernadotte married Swedish actress [[Marianne Bernadotte|Marianne Lindberg Tchang]] on 30 July 1961.\n\n==Title==\nBernadotte was born Prince of Sweden and Duke of Uppland, but having made an [[Royal intermarriage#Morganatic marriage|unequal match]] was disqualified from the [[Line of succession to the Swedish throne|line of succession]]. He was also forbidden to use his birth titles<ref>[[Gunnar Bramst\u00e5ng]] in ''''Tronr\u00e4tt, b\u00f6rdstitel och hustillh\u00f6righet'' {{ISBN|91-544-2081-4}} p. 54-55</ref> and left to be called ''Mr. Bernadotte''. His cousin [[Lennart Bernadotte]], who two years earlier had experienced the same thing (as the first Swede in history), considered himself, and even more so Sigvard, subjected to very cruel treatment for several decades by the [[Royal Court of Sweden]] due to their marriages.<ref>[[Lennart Bernadotte]] in ''Mainau min medelpunkt'' {{ISBN|91-0-056122-3}} p. 77</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 1951, for himself, his wife and his marital descendants, Bernadotte was admitted by [[Grand Duchess Charlotte of Luxembourg|Grand Duchess Charlotte]] ([[head of state]] at the time) into the nobility of Luxembourg with the title [[Count of Wisborg]].<ref name=\"OAF\">{{cite book|editor1-last=von Rothstein|editor1-first=Niclas|title=Kalender \u00f6ver Ointroducerad adels f\u00f6rening|date=2009|publisher=[[Ointroducerad Adels F\u00f6rening]]|isbn=9789163350382|page=22|edition=22nd|language=Swedish}}</ref> and in that conferral was also called ''Sigvard Oscar Frederik Prince Bernadotte''.<ref>''[[M\u00e9morial]] du Grand-Duch\u00e9 de Luxembourg [http://data.legilux.public.lu/file/eli-etat-leg-memorial-1951-48-fr-pdf.pdf]'', Government of Luxembourg, 13 August 1951, entry dated 18 July 1951, p. 1135</ref> \n\nAfter more than 30 years of argument and controversy in Sweden over his rank and titles, problems which worsened when his father died in 1973, and fed up after having been demonstratively snubbed by the Royal Court of Sweden during a state visit by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] in 1983, Bernadotte announced to [[Tidningarnas Telegrambyr\u00e5]] on 28 May of that year that he was to be known as ''Prince Sigvard Bernadotte'' from then on.<ref>[[Marianne Bernadotte]] in ''Glimtar och scener'' [[Norstedts]] Stockholm 1986 {{ISBN|91-1-863442-7}} pp. 161 & 175-179: entire paragraph</ref>\n\nOver the years since then, based on precedent established in 1888 for his great-uncle [[Prince Oscar Bernadotte|Oscar]],<ref>[https://www.svd.se/lang-kamp-for-prinstitel-forgaves Article] by Anita Bergmark in ''[[Svenska Dagbladet]]'' 2002-05-02</ref> and citing Oscar's title of nobility as it was confirmed by the Government of Luxembourg in 1892, Bernadotte was supported by several legal experts<ref>[http://wwwc.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/0105/14/kung.html Article] by Petter Ovander in ''[[Aftonbladet]]'' 2001-05-14 quoting three attorneys</ref> when he petitioned for acknowledgement in Sweden of the ''[[Prince Bernadotte]]'' title as his also,<ref>Roger Lundgren in ''[[Princess Sibylla of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Sibylla]], en biografi'' [[Bonniers]] {{ISBN|9789100111120}} p. 108, specifically naming that title as what Sigvard wanted acknowledged</ref> although he did not seek reinstatement in the line of succession to the throne as a royal prince of that country. [[Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden|King Carl XVI Gustaf]] has been criticized for never obliging and for his consequent estrangement from his uncle.<ref>[https://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/ Article] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810205908/https://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/ |date=2017-08-10 }} by Scott Ritcher in ''[[The Local]]'' 2009-12-23</ref>\n\nBernadotte went to the [[European Court of Human Rights]] in an effort to have the Government of Sweden acknowledge his princely title there, but in 2004, after his death, the ECHR declared the application inadmissible.<ref>[http://cmiskp.echr.coe.int/tkp197/view.asp?item=1&action=html&sessionid=94512204 ]{{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe wording on his gravestone, at the [[Kungliga begravningsplatsen|Royal Cemetery]], which is owned by the king, does make it clear that he was \"born Prince of Sweden\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Sigvard Bernadotte|url=http://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/|accessdate=2 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202215105/http://www.thelocal.se/blogs/snuggling/2009/12/23/sigvard-bernadotte/|archivedate=2 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1994 to 2002, he was the oldest living great-grandchild of [[Queen Victoria|Queen Victoria of the United Kingdom]], and having reached the age of 94, he was her longest-lived male descendant until being overtaken by his younger brother [[Count Carl Johan Bernadotte of Wisborg|Carl Johan]] on 29 June 2011.\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nBlason du Prince Sigvard duc d'Uppland.svg|Sigvard's arms as Prince of Sweden and Duke of Uppland\nArms of Prince Bernadotte 1951 Luxembourg.jpg|Arms as described by the Government of Luxembourg for [[Prince Bernadotte|Princes and Princesses Bernadotte]] in 1951\nArmoiries de Lennart Bernadotte comte de Wisborg.svg|Arms of the [[Count of Wisborg|Counts of Wisborg]]<ref name=\"OAF\"/>\n</gallery>\n\n== Ancestry ==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Sigvard Bernadotte, Count of Wisborg'''\n|2= 2. [[Gustaf VI Adolf of Sweden]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Margaret of Connaught]]\n|4= 4. [[Gustaf V of Sweden]]\n|5= 5. [[Victoria of Baden|Princess Victoria of Baden]]\n|6= 6. [[Prince Arthur, Duke of Connaught and Strathearn]]\n|7= 7. [[Princess Louise Margaret of Prussia]]\n|8= 8. [[Oscar II of Sweden]]\n|9= 9. [[Sophia of Nassau|Princess Sophia of Nassau]]\n|10= 10. [[Frederick I, Grand Duke of Baden]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Louise of Prussia]]\n|12= 12. [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha]]\n|13= 13. [[Queen Victoria|Victoria, Queen of the United Kingdom]]\n|14= 14. [[Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia (1828\u201385)|Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia]]\n|15= 15. [[Princess Maria Anna of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Swedish Act of Succession]]\n* [[Instrument of Government (1809)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0076027|name=Sigvard Bernadotte}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Bernadotte]]|7 June|1907|4 February|2002}}\n{{S-roy|se}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Uppland|Duke of Uppland]] | before=[[Prince Gustaf, Duke of Uppland|Prince Gustaf]] | after=none | years=}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{House of Bernadotte}}\n{{Swedish princes}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bernadotte, Sigvard}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Stockholm]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Uppland|Uppland]]\n[[Category:Swedish memoirists]]\n[[Category:Swedish princes|Sigvard 1907]]\n[[Category:Swedish industrial designers]]\n[[Category:Uppsala University alumni]]\n[[Category:House of Bernadotte|Sigvard]]\n[[Category:Swedish people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Burials at Kungliga begravningsplatsen|Sigvard]]\n[[Category:Disinherited European royalty]]\n[[Category:Counts of Wisborg|Sigvard]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Prince Eugen Medal]]\n[[Category:Princes Bernadotte|Sigvard]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigvard_Bernadotte"}
{"title_page": "Negative pressure ventilator", "text_new": "{{short description|Medical technology}}\nA '''negative pressure ventilator''' (NPV) is a type of [[mechanical ventilator]] that stimulates an ill person's [[breathing]] by applying negative air pressure to their body. \n\n==Description==\n[[File:Iron lung action diagrams.png|thumb|Iron lung cylinder (black), patient head exposed through sealed opening. Diaphragm (yellow) mechanically extends, and then retracts -- varying cylinder air pressure -- causing patient chest to expand (inhale) (top), and then contract (exhaling) (bottom)]]\n\nIn most NPVs (such as the [[iron lung]] in diagram at right), the negative pressure is applied to the patient's torso, to cause their chest to expand, expanding their lungs, drawing air into the patient's lungs through their [[airway]].<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\">Grum, Cyril M., MD, and Melvin L. Morganroth, MD, [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.980.7916&rep=rep1&type=pdf \"Initiating Mechanical Ventilation,\"] in ''[[Intensive Care Medicine]]'' 1988;3:6-20, retrieved April 12, 2020</ref><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\">Rockoff, Mark, M.D., [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cUCqsl6JROg \"The Iron Lung and Polio,\"], video (8 minutes), January 11, 2016, OPENPediatrics and [[Boston Children's Hospital]] on [[YouTube]], retrieved April 11, 2020 (historical background and images, explanatory diagrams, and live demonstrations)</ref><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\">[https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects-and-stories/medicine/iron-lung \"The Iron Lung,\"] [[Science Museum Group]], Kensington, [[London, England]], U.K. (moderately detailed, illustrated description of the device and its application -- and history), retrieved April 11, 2020</ref><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\">\n[https://www.newsweek.com/how-does-iron-lung-work-polio-survivor-last-us-1083104 \"How Does Iron Lung Work?: Polio Survivor, 82, Among Last to Use Breathing Equipment,\"] August 21, 2018, ''[[Newsweek]]'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref><ref name=\"what_is_the_background_2019_04_11medscape\">Jackson, Christopher D., MD, Dept. of Internal Medicine, and Muthiah P Muthiah, MD, FCCP, D-ABSM, Assoc. Prof. of Medicine, Div. of Pulmonary / Critical Care / Sleep Medicine, [[University of Tennessee|Univ. of Tennessee]] College of Medicine-Memphis, et.al., [https://www.medscape.com/answers/304068-104770/what-is-the-background-of-the-iron-lung-form-of-mechanical-ventilation \"What is the background of the iron lung form of mechanical ventilation?,\"] April 11, 2019, Medscape, retrieved April 12, 2020</ref>\n\nAnother form of NPV device (such as the Pulmotor) is placed at the patient's airway, and alternates negative pressure with [[Positive-pressure respiration|''positive'' pressure]] -- to pump air into their lungs (inhale under positive pressure), then suck it back out (exhale under negative pressure).<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"first_mechanical_ventilator_2017_bottrell\">Bottrell, John, (registered respiratory therapist), [http://asthmahistory.blogspot.com/2017/04/1907-first-mechanical-ventilator.html \"1907: The first mechanical ventilator: The Pulmotor,\"] April 19, 2017, ''Asthma History'' blog, retrieved April 12, 2020</ref><ref name=\"draeger_pulmotor_wood_library_museum\">[https://www.woodlibrarymuseum.org/museum/item/96/draeger-pulmotor \"Draeger Pulmotor\"], [[Wood Library-Museum of Anesthesiology]]</ref><ref name=\"return_of_the_pulmotor\">[https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1943Sci....98..547H/abstract \"The Return of the Pulmotor as a 'Resuscitator': A Back-Step toward the Death of Thousands,\"] by Yandell Henderson, December 1943, ''[[Science (journal)|Science]].''</ref><ref name=\"it_began_with_the_pulmotor\">Bahns, Ernst,  [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download;jsessionid=35715024EB705379BC527B436562F16D?doi=10.1.1.630.5641&rep=rep1&type=pdf ''It began with the Pulmotor: One Hundred Years of Artificial Ventilation''], [[Dr\u00e4ger (company) |Dr\u00e4ger Medical AG & Co. KG]], L\u00fcbeck, Germany (original manufacturers of the Pulmotor).</ref>\n\n==Types of NPVs==\nThere are (or have been) several types of NPVs, including:<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\n* '''[[Iron lung]]''' - The first common pure-NPV device -- originally developed in the 1920s by Drinker, Shaw and Mason -- it is a large, sealed horizontal cylinder (or \"tank\") in which the patient lays, with their head protruding from a sealed opening at one end of the tank. A flexible [[diaphragm]] (typicaly at the other end of the cylinder) is mechanically actuated to expand and contract, in continuous alternations, thereby continuously lowering and raising the air pressure in the cylinder. This causes the patient's chest to rise and fall, stimulating inhalation and exhalation through the patient's nose and mouth (outside the cylinder).<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"what_is_the_background_2019_04_11medscape\" />\n* '''Cuirass ventilator''' also known as \"chest shell\" or \"turtle shell\" - A more compact variation of the iron lung, which only encloses the patient's torso, and is sealed around their neck and waist.<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" />\n* '''exovent''' - a modern device similar to the Cuirass ventilator, but developed in 2020, in response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\">[https://newatlas.com/medical/british-engineers-modern-iron-lung-covid-19-ventilator-alternative/ \"Modern iron lung designed to address ventilator shortage,\"], April 06, 2020, ''[[New Atlas]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020 (note detailed reader comment, , April 7, 2020, by Christopher Smith, with clinical application details.)</ref><ref name=\"iron_lung_and_2020_04_11_oxy_gen\">[http://oxygen.milano.it/en/the-iron-lung-and-the-modern-ventilation/ \"The 'iron lung' and the modern 'ventilation',\"] Oxy.gen, \nretrieved April 11, 2020 (caution: source unclear; apparently an Italian oxygen-supplier)</ref> \n* '''Poncho ventilator''' - An inflatable version of the iron lung or the Cuirass ventilator, constructed of an inflatable material (such as plastic or rubber) arranged over a light metal frame or screen.<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" />\n\n...and PPV/NPVs, including:\n* '''Pulmotor''' - brand name for a device developed in the early 1900s that was the forerunner of modern [[mechanical ventilator]]s. It used pressure from a tank of compressed oxygen to operate a valve system that alternately forced air into and out of a person's airway, using alternating positive and negative air pressure<ref name=\"first_mechanical_ventilator_2017_bottrell\" /><ref name=\"draeger_pulmotor_wood_library_museum\" /><ref name=\"return_of_the_pulmotor\" /><ref name=\"it_began_with_the_pulmotor\" />\n\n==Usage==\nNegative pressure ventilators -- while widely used in the early-to-mid 20th Century (particularly for victims of the [[Polio#History|Polio epidemics]]) -- are now largely replaced by [[Positive-pressure airway ventilator]]s, which force air (or oxygen) directly into the patient's airway.<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download;jsessionid=35715024EB705379BC527B436562F16D?doi=10.1.1.630.5641&rep=rep1&type=pdf ''It began with the Pulmotor: One Hundred Years of Artificial Ventilation''] by Ernst Bahns, published by [[Dr\u00e4ger (company) |Dr\u00e4ger Medical AG & Co. KG]], L\u00fcbeck, Germany (original manufacturers of the Pulmotor, and many other ventilation items, to the present day) (a lengthy, illustrated history of the development of artificial ventilation, interwoven with the publishers' own apparently self-promotional corporate history).\n\n\n\n[[Category:Respiratory therapy]]\n[[Category:Mechanical ventilation]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Medical technology}}\nA '''negative pressure ventilator''' (NPV) is a type of [[mechanical ventilator]] that stimulates an ill person's [[breathing]] by applying negative air pressure to their body. \n\n==Description==\n[[File:Iron lung action diagrams.png|thumb|Iron lung cylinder (black), patient head exposed through sealed opening. Diaphragm (yellow) mechanically extends, and then retracts -- varying cylinder air pressure -- causing patient chest to expand (inhale) (top), and then contract (exhaling) (bottom)]]\n\nIn most NPVs (such as the [[iron lung]] in diagram at right), the negative pressure is applied to the patient's torso, to cause their chest to expand, expanding their lungs, drawing air into the patient's lungs through their [[airway]].<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\">Grum, Cyril M., MD, and Melvin L. Morganroth, MD, [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.980.7916&rep=rep1&type=pdf \"Initiating Mechanical Ventilation,\"] in ''[[Intensive Care Medicine]]'' 1988;3:6-20, retrieved April 12, 2020</ref><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\">Rockoff, Mark, M.D., [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cUCqsl6JROg \"The Iron Lung and Polio,\"], video (8 minutes), January 11, 2016, OPENPediatrics and [[Boston Children's Hospital]] on [[YouTube]], retrieved April 11, 2020 (historical background and images, explanatory diagrams, and live demonstrations)</ref><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\">[https://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/objects-and-stories/medicine/iron-lung \"The Iron Lung,\"] [[Science Museum Group]], Kensington, [[London, England]], U.K. (moderately detailed, illustrated description of the device and its application -- and history), retrieved April 11, 2020</ref><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\">\n[https://www.newsweek.com/how-does-iron-lung-work-polio-survivor-last-us-1083104 \"How Does Iron Lung Work?: Polio Survivor, 82, Among Last to Use Breathing Equipment,\"] August 21, 2018, ''[[Newsweek]]'' retrieved April 11, 2020</ref>\n\nAnother form of NPV device (such as the Pulmotor) is placed at the patient's airway, and alternates negative pressure with [[Positive-pressure respiration|''positive'' pressure]] -- to pump air into their lungs (inhale under positive pressure), then suck it back out (exhale under negative pressure).<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"first_mechanical_ventilator_2017_bottrell\">Bottrell, John, (registered respiratory therapist), [http://asthmahistory.blogspot.com/2017/04/1907-first-mechanical-ventilator.html \"1907: The first mechanical ventilator: The Pulmotor,\"] April 19, 2017, ''Asthma History'' blog, retrieved April 12, 2020</ref><ref name=\"draeger_pulmotor_wood_library_museum\">[https://www.woodlibrarymuseum.org/museum/item/96/draeger-pulmotor \"Draeger Pulmotor\"], [[Wood Library-Museum of Anesthesiology]]</ref><ref name=\"return_of_the_pulmotor\">[https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1943Sci....98..547H/abstract \"The Return of the Pulmotor as a 'Resuscitator': A Back-Step toward the Death of Thousands,\"] by Yandell Henderson, December 1943, ''[[Science (journal)|Science]].''</ref><ref name=\"it_began_with_the_pulmotor\">Bahns, Ernst,  [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download;jsessionid=35715024EB705379BC527B436562F16D?doi=10.1.1.630.5641&rep=rep1&type=pdf ''It began with the Pulmotor: One Hundred Years of Artificial Ventilation''], [[Dr\u00e4ger (company) |Dr\u00e4ger Medical AG & Co. KG]], L\u00fcbeck, Germany (original manufacturers of the Pulmotor).</ref>\n\n==Types of NPVs==\nThere are (or have been) several types of NPVs, including:<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\n* '''[[Iron lung]]''' - The first common pure-NPV device -- originally developed in the 1920s by Drinker, Shaw and Mason -- it is a large, sealed horizontal cylinder (or \"tank\") in which the patient lays, with their head protruding from a sealed opening at one end of the tank. A flexible [[diaphragm]] (typicaly at the other end of the cylinder) is mechanically actuated to expand and contract, in continuous alternations, thereby continuously lowering and raising the air pressure in the cylinder. This causes the patient's chest to rise and fall, stimulating inhalation and exhalation through the patient's nose and mouth (outside the cylinder).<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"what_is_the_background_2019_04_11medscape\">Jackson, Christopher D., MD, Dept. of Internal Medicine, and Muthiah P Muthiah, MD, FCCP, D-ABSM, Assoc. Prof. of Medicine, Div. of Pulmonary / Critical Care / Sleep Medicine, [[University of Tennessee|Univ. of Tennessee]] College of Medicine-Memphis, et.al., [https://www.medscape.com/answers/304068-104770/what-is-the-background-of-the-iron-lung-form-of-mechanical-ventilation \"What is the background of the iron lung form of mechanical ventilation?,\"] April 11, 2019, Medscape, retrieved April 12, 2020</ref>\n* '''Cuirass ventilator''' also known as \"chest shell\" or \"turtle shell\" - A more compact variation of the iron lung, which only encloses the patient's torso, and is sealed around their neck and waist.<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" />\n* '''exovent''' - a modern device similar to the Cuirass ventilator, but developed in 2020, in response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name=\"modern_iron_lung_2020_04_06_newatlas\">[https://newatlas.com/medical/british-engineers-modern-iron-lung-covid-19-ventilator-alternative/ \"Modern iron lung designed to address ventilator shortage,\"], April 06, 2020, ''[[New Atlas]],'' retrieved April 11, 2020 (note detailed reader comment, , April 7, 2020, by Christopher Smith, with clinical application details.)</ref><ref name=\"iron_lung_and_2020_04_11_oxy_gen\">[http://oxygen.milano.it/en/the-iron-lung-and-the-modern-ventilation/ \"The 'iron lung' and the modern 'ventilation',\"] Oxy.gen, \nretrieved April 11, 2020 (caution: source unclear; apparently an Italian oxygen-supplier)</ref> \n* '''Poncho ventilator''' - An inflatable version of the iron lung or the Cuirass ventilator, constructed of an inflatable material (such as plastic or rubber) arranged over a light metal frame or screen.<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" />\n\n...and PPV/NPVs, including:\n* '''Pulmotor''' - brand name for a device developed in the early 1900s that was the forerunner of modern [[mechanical ventilator]]s. It used pressure from a tank of compressed oxygen to operate a valve system that alternately forced air into and out of a person's airway, using alternating positive and negative air pressure<ref name=\"first_mechanical_ventilator_2017_bottrell\" /><ref name=\"draeger_pulmotor_wood_library_museum\" /><ref name=\"return_of_the_pulmotor\" /><ref name=\"it_began_with_the_pulmotor\" />\n\n==Usage==\nNegative pressure ventilators -- while widely used in the early-to-mid 20th Century (particularly for victims of the [[Polio#History|Polio epidemics]]) -- are now largely replaced by [[Positive-pressure airway ventilator]]s, which force air (or oxygen) directly into the patient's airway.<ref name=\"initiating_1988_3_intensive_care_med\" /><ref name=\"iron_lung_2016_01_11_openpediatrics_you_tube\" /><ref name=\"the_iron_lung_sciencemuseum_org_uk\" /><ref name=\"how_does_iron_lung_work_2018_08_21_newsweek\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download;jsessionid=35715024EB705379BC527B436562F16D?doi=10.1.1.630.5641&rep=rep1&type=pdf ''It began with the Pulmotor: One Hundred Years of Artificial Ventilation''] by Ernst Bahns, published by [[Dr\u00e4ger (company) |Dr\u00e4ger Medical AG & Co. KG]], L\u00fcbeck, Germany (original manufacturers of the Pulmotor, and many other ventilation items, to the present day) (a lengthy, illustrated history of the development of artificial ventilation, interwoven with the publishers' own apparently self-promotional corporate history).\n\n\n\n[[Category:Respiratory therapy]]\n[[Category:Mechanical ventilation]]\n", "name_user": "Penlite", "label": "safe", "comment": "move ref cite <ref name=\"what_is_the_background_2019_04_11medscape\">", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_pressure_ventilator"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sweden}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in [[Sweden]]\n| map1            = COVID-19_Outbreak_Cases_in_Sweden_by_Number_with_Legend.svg\n| legend1         = {{Center|Map of confirmed cases in Sweden\n(absolute numbers)<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/>\n}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Sweden]]\n| first_case      = [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]]\n| arrival_date    = 24 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=24|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| deaths          = 1,033<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/> as of 14 April \n| confirmed_cases = 11,445<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/> as of 14 April\n| severe_cases    = 915<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/> in [[intensive care unit|ICU]] as of 14 April\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/ Swedish Public Health Agency Covid-19] (''in Swedish'')\n}}\n<!-- General overview -->\n\nThe [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing pandemic]] of [[COVID-19|coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2), was confirmed to have reached [[Sweden]] on 31 January 2020, when a woman returning from [[Wuhan]] tested positive. On 26 February, following outbreaks [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|in Italy]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran|in Iran]], multiple travel-related clusters appeared in Sweden. [[Transmission (medicine)#Definition and related terms|Community transmission]] was confirmed on 9 March in the [[Stockholm Regional Council|Stockholm region]]. Since then, individuals in every [[Counties of Sweden|l\u00e4n (county)]] have tested positive for COVID-19. The first death was reported on 11 March in [[Stockholm]], a case of community transmission.\n<!-- References in main text, not lead--><!-- Restrictions -->\n\nSweden has, unlike many other countries, not applied any [[lockdown]], with most measures being voluntary. The [[Swedish Constitution|Swedish constitution]] prohibits [[Ministerstyre|ministerial rule]] and mandates that the relevant government body, here an expert agency \u2014 the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden|Public Health Agency]] \u2014 must initiate all actions to prevent the virus. The government can follow agency recommendations, as it has with legislation limiting [[freedom of assembly]], temporarily banning gatherings of over 50 individuals, banning people from visiting nursing homes, as well as physically closing [[secondary school]]s and [[University|universities]].<!--Reference in text--> Primary schools have remained open, in part to avoid healthcare workers staying home with their children.<!-- References in main text, not lead--><!-- Recommendations and health care changes -->\n\nThe Public Health Agency and government issued recommendations to: if possible, work from home; avoid unnecessary travel within the country; to engage in [[social distancing]]; and for people above 70 to stay at home, as much as possible. Those with even minimal symptoms which could be COVID-19, are recommended to stay home. The '[[Sick leave#Sweden|''karensdag'']]' or initial day without paid [[Sick leave|sick-leave]] has been removed by the government and the length of time one can stay home with pay without a doctor's note has been raised from 7 to 21 days.<!-- References in main text, not lead--><!-- Case number-->\n\n{{As of|2020|4|14|df=EU}}, there were 11,445 confirmed cases, of which 915 received intensive care, and 1,033 deaths related to the newly found virus in Sweden, with [[Stockholm County]] being the most affected.<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\">{{Cite web|url=https://experience.arcgis.com/experience/09f821667ce64bf7be6f9f87457ed9aa|title=Antal fall av covid-19 i Sverige - data uppdateras dagligen kl 11.30|last=|first=|date=2020-03-30|website=Public Health Agency of Sweden \u2014 Official statistics at arcgis|publisher=[[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] (Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09|layurl=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/aktuellt-epidemiologiskt-lage/|laysource=Antal fall av covid-19 \u2014 Statistik \u2013 antal fall covid-19|language=Swedish|quote=\"Data updated daily at 11:30 [CET]\"}}</ref><!-- Reference added for statement that is subject to frequent change-->\n\nOn the 10th of April the number of confirmed cases reached 10,000 and on the 13th of April the death toll reached 1,000.\n\n==Background==\n{{Further|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#History}}\nOn 12 January, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] (nCoV) was the cause of a [[COVID-19|respiratory illness]] in a cluster of people in [[Wuhan]], in [[Hubei|Hubei province]], [[China]], who had initially come to the WHO's attention on 31 December 2019. This cluster was initially linked to the [[Huanan Seafood Wholesale Market]] in Wuhan City.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A few days later, on 16 January, the [[Swedish Public Health Agency]] issued a press release highlighting the discovery of the novel coronavirus, and the agency monitoring the situation. The risk of spread to Sweden was described as \"very low\" as there was yet no evidence that the virus [[transmission (medicine)|could spread between humans]], but they recommended that individuals developing [[cough]] or [[fever]] after visiting Wuhan should seek medical care, and asked for healthcare professionals to be observant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/januari/nytt-coronavirus-upptackt-i-kina/|title=Nytt coronavirus uppt\u00e4ckt i Kina \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the World Health Organization classified the novel Coronavirus as a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]] on 30 January and demanded that all member states should cooperate to prevent further spread of the virus, the Agency requested for the Swedish government to classify the novel disease as a [[notifiable disease|notifiable infectious disease]] in the [[Notifiable diseases in Sweden|Swedish Communicable Diseases Act]] as both [[Notifiable diseases in Sweden#List of notifiable diseases|dangerous to public health]] (allm\u00e4nfarlig) and [[Notifiable diseases in Sweden#List of notifiable diseases|dangerous to society]] (samh\u00e4llsfarlig), where [[contact tracing]] is required,<ref name=fhmpress200131>{{cite web |title=Utbrottet av nytt coronavirus kr\u00e4ver samordnade insatser internationellt \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/januari/utbrottet-av-nytt-coronavirus-kraver-samordnade-insatser-internationellt/ |website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=sv |date=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten f\u00f6resl\u00e5r att nytt coronavirus tas upp i smittskyddslagen \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/januari/folkhalsomyndigheten-foreslar-att-nytt-coronavirus-tas-upp-i-smittskyddslagen/ |website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Blohm |first1=Lisa |title=Coronavirus p\u00e5 v\u00e4g klassas som samh\u00e4llsfarligt |url=https://www.dagensmedicin.se/artiklar/2020/01/31/coronavirus-pa-vag-klassas-som-samhallsfarligt/ |website=Dagens Medicin |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref> giving the disease the same legislative status as [[Ebola]], [[SARS]] and [[Smallpox]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Anm\u00e4lningspliktiga sjukdomar \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/overvakning-och-rapportering/anmalningspliktiga-sjukdomar/ |website=www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=3 March 2020}}</ref> The agency also announced that they have [[ COVID-19 testing|analysing methods]] that can diagnose a case of the novel disease \u2018within hours\u2019 after testing, and that such tests had already been carried out, but that all had turned out negative.<ref name=fhmpress200131 />\n\n===Preparedness===\nIn the [[Global Health Security Index|2019 Global Health Security Index]] published by the [[Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security]], Sweden was considered to be one of the \u2018most prepared\u2019 countries in the world for an epidemic or a pandemic, ranking 7th overall. Sweden was considered to be among the countries most capable of preventing the emergence of a new pathogen, early detection of an epidemic and reporting an epidemic of international concern and having a low risk environment. However, the [[Healthcare in Sweden|Swedish health system]] received a lower score, questioning if it was sufficient and robust enough to treat the sick and protect health workers.<ref>{{cite web |title=GHS Index: Findings and Recommendations |url=https://www.ghsindex.org/ |accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBefore the outbreak of the new coronavirus, Sweden had a relatively low [[List of countries by hospital beds|number of hospital beds per capita]], with 2.2 beds per 1000 people (2017),<ref>{{cite web|title=Health Care Resources|url=http://stats.oecd.org/index.aspx?DataSetCode=HEALTH_REAC#|website=stats.oecd.org|accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref> and an [[List of countries by hospital beds#Numbers|intensive care unit (ICU) beds per capita]] of 5.8 per 100.000 people.<ref name=\"Rhodes2012\">{{Cite journal |last=Rhodes |first=A. |last2=Ferdinande |first2=P. |last3=Flaatten |first3=H. |last4=Guidet |first4=B. |last5=Metnitz |first5=P. G. |last6=Moreno |first6=R. P. |date=2012-10-01 |title=The variability of critical care bed numbers in Europe |journal=Intensive Care Medicine |language=en |volume=38 |issue=10 |pages=1647\u20131653 |doi=10.1007/s00134-012-2627-8 |pmid=22777516 |issn=1432-1238}}</ref> Both numbers were lower than most countries in the [[European Union|EU]]. The total number of ICU beds in Swedish hospitals were 526.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frejdeman |first1=Hannah |title=\u201dEfterrapportering att v\u00e4nta efter helgen\u201d |url=https://www.svd.se/just-nu-folkhalsomyndigheten-haller-presstraff |website=Svenska Dagbladet |language=sv |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Sweden medical cases chart}}\n<!-- NOTICE\n     Keep this section short!\n     Sections below are\n     more detailed.\n     Minor details can\n     be added to the\n     timeline below! -->\nOn 31 January, the first Swedish case was confirmed in a woman in [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]] who had travelled to Sweden from Wuhan on 24 January directly from Wuhan. The case was fully isolated and there are no reports of further spread.<ref name=\"fhm0226\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gp.se/1.24829340|title=F\u00f6rsta svenska coronafallet kliniskt frisk|last=Abrahamsson|first=Anders|date=3 March 2020|website=gp.se|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The second case was diagnosed at [[Sahlgrenska University Hospital]], [[Gothenburg]] on 26 February, after a man who had recently returned from northern [[Italy]] following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|COVID-19 outbreak in Italy]] had developed symptoms.<ref name=\"bolin1\">{{Cite news|last=Bolin|first=Mattias|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/vast/bekraftat-coronafall-i-goteborg-person-vardas-pa-sahlgrenska|title=Bekr\u00e4ftat coronafall i G\u00f6teborg \u2013 person v\u00e5rdas p\u00e5 Sahlgrenska|date=26 February 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=26 February 2020|language=sv}}</ref><ref name=\"fhm0226\">{{cite web|url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/februari/nytt-bekraftat-fall-av-covid-19/|title=Nytt bekr\u00e4ftat fall av covid-19|date=26 February 2020|website=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|language=sv|trans-title=New confirmed case of covid-19|url-status=live|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref> With five additional cases confirmed on 27 February,<ref>https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/februari/inbjudan-till-presstraff-ytterligare-fall-av-covid-19-i-flera-regioner2/</ref> the Swedish Public Health Agency ('''Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten''<nowiki/>') put out a statement that these cases were all related to travel to high-risk zones and that there was no evidence of [[Transmission (medicine)|community transmission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/februari/inbjudan-till-presstraff-ytterligare-fall-av-covid-19-i-flera-regioner2/|title=Inbjudan till presstr\u00e4ff: Ytterligare fall av covid-19 i flera regioner \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Disease control measures, including extensive [[contact tracing]] turned up over 200 travel-related cases in the following weeks, all with connection to confirmed cases or travel to high risk regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/snabbkollen/30-40-i-karantan-pa-stockholmssjukhus|title=M\u00f6jliga fall av inhemsk smitta|date=9 March 2020|website=svt.se|url-status=live|access-date=27 March 2020|language=sv|trans-title=Possible cases of domestic infection}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February, [[Uppsala County]] confirmed its first case in a woman with a travel history to Germany, where she had met with an Italian colleague, and had been admitted to [[Uppsala University Hospital]]<ref name=\"Via TT\">{{cite web|url=https://via.tt.se/embedded/release/patient-med-bekraftat-coronavirus-vardas-pa-akademiska?publisherId=3235664&releaseId=3271133|title=Via TT|website=via.tt.se|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref> after seeking medical attention with flu-like symptoms. [[Halland County|Halland]], [[Norrbotten County|Norrbotten]], [[S\u00f6dermanland County|S\u00f6dermanland]],[[V\u00e4sterbotten County|V\u00e4sterbotten]] and [[\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland County|\u00d6sterg\u00f6tland]] all confirmed their first cases on 9 March.,<ref name=\"news - Region Halland\" /><ref name=\"Bekr\u00e4ftat fall av coronavirus i S\u00f6r\">{{cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/sormland/bekraftat-fall-av-coronavirus-i-sormland|title=Bekr\u00e4ftat fall av coronavirus i S\u00f6rmland|last=|first=|date=|website=SVT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"SVT9\">{{cite news|last1=Larsson|first1=Erica|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/norrbotten/forsta-coronafallet-i-norrbotten|title=F\u00f6rsta coronafallet konstaterat i Norrbotten|date=9 March 2020|access-date=11 March 2020|publisher=Sveriges Television|last2=Haupt|first2=Inger|language=Swedish}}</ref><ref name=\"vasterbotten0309\">{{cite web|url=https://www.regionvasterbotten.se/bekraftade-fall-av-coronavirus-i-vasterbotten|title=Bekr\u00e4ftade fall av coronavirus i V\u00e4sterbotten|website=Region V\u00e4sterbotten|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"regionostergotland.se\" /><ref name=\"SVT9\"/> This came as the first cases of community transmission was confirmed among two patients who had sought care at [[Saint G\u00f6ran Hospital|S:t G\u00f6ran Hospital]], [[Stockholm]], on 6 March.<ref name=\"20employees\">{{Cite news|last=Erlandsson|first=\u00c5sa|url=https://www.svd.se/coronasmittad-pa-st-goran--personal-satt-i-karantan|title=20 anst\u00e4llda i karant\u00e4n \u2013 S:t G\u00f6rans i stabsl\u00e4ge|date=9 March 2020|work=Svenska Dagbladet|access-date=9 March 2020|language=sv|trans-title=20 employees in quarantine - S: t G\u00f6rans in staff position|issn=1101-2412}}</ref> They were assumed to have been infected through community transmission approximately 7 days before seeking care.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} The following day, [[J\u00e4mtland County|J\u00e4mtland]] and [[V\u00e4sternorrland County|V\u00e4sternorrland]] also confirmed initial cases.<ref name=\"regionjh.se\">{{cite web|url=https://www.regionjh.se/nyheter/pressmeddelanden/rjhpress/enpersonijamtlandslankonstateratsmittadavcoronaviruset.5.55412b91170402c7d222e632.html|title=En person i J\u00e4mtlands l\u00e4n konstaterat smittad av coronaviruset - Region J\u00e4mtland H\u00e4rjedalen|website=regionjh.se|language=sv|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"rvn.se\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rvn.se/sv/Om-regionen/Aktuellt-i-Region-Vasternorrland/Nyheter/tre-personer-i-vasternorrland-smittade-av-coronaviruset/|title=Tre personer i V\u00e4sternorrland smittade av coronaviruset|website=rvn.se|language=sv|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nResponding to indications of local transmission in the [[Stockholm county|Stockholm]] area and [[V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland County|V\u00e4stra G\u00f6taland]], the Public Health Agency on 10 March raised the risk assessment of community spread from ''moderate'' to ''very high'', which is the highest level.<ref name=\"folkhalsomyndigheten.se\">{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/flera-tecken-pa-samhallsspridning-av-covid-19-i-sverige/|title=Flera tecken p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llsspridning av covid-19 i Sverige \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"folkhalsomyndigheten.se\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Stefansson|first=Klara|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/risken-for-coronaspridning-i-sverige-hojs-till-mycket-hog|title=Risken f\u00f6r coronaspridning i Sverige h\u00f6js till \"mycket h\u00f6g\"|date=10 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=10 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/flera-tecken-pa-samhallsspridning-av-covid-19-i-sverige/|title=Flera tecken p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llsspridning av Covid-19 i Sverige|last=|first=|date=|website=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=10 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The first death was reported on 11 March, when a person in their 70s from the Stockholm region died in the intensive care unit of [[Karolinska University Hospital]]. The person was reported to have acquired the virus through community transmission, believed to have occurred about one week before death. The person also belonged to a risk group.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite news|last=Claesson|first=Frida|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/stockholm/en-person-har-avlidit-av-coronaviruset|title=En person har avlidit till f\u00f6ljd av coronaviruset|date=11 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=11 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nThe COVID-19 outbreak, which the World Health Organization (WHO) declared a pandemic on 11 March,<ref name=\"nyt sports\">{{Cite news|last=Deb|first=Sopan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/11/sports/basketball/warriors-coronavirus-fans.html|title=Sports Leagues Bar Fans and Cancel Games Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|date=11 March 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=12 March 2020|last2=Cacciola|first2=Scott|issn=0362-4331|last3=Stein|first3=Marc}}</ref> has had a disparate impact on different areas of Sweden.\n\nThe Public Health Agency of Sweden declared on 13 March that stopping the spread of Covid-19 has entered a \"new phase\" which requires \"other efforts\". The continued focus is now to delay spread among the population and to protect the elderly and most vulnerable against the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/ny-fas-kraver-nya-insatser-mot-covid-19/|title=Ny fas kr\u00e4ver nya insatser mot covid-19 \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe health agency believed that 5-10% of the population in Stockholm County were carrying the virus on 9 April.<ref Name=mellan5och10>{{cite web |last1=Zachrisson |first1=Lotta |title=Tegnell: \"Mellan fem och tio procent b\u00e4r p\u00e5 viruset\" |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/ny-studie-2-5-av-stockholmarna-bar-pa-viruset |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=sv |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government policy==\nThe [[Government of Sweden#Present Cabinet|Swedish government]] has tried to focus efforts on encouraging the right behaviour and creating social norms rather than mandatory restrictions. Government officials including [[Prime Minister of Sweden|Swedish prime minister]] [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]], as well as the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] have encouraged each individual to take responsibility for their own health and the health of others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/ewa-stenberg-lofven-vill-hellre-overtyga-an-forbjuda/|title=Ewa Stenberg: L\u00f6fven vill hellre \u00f6vertyga \u00e4n f\u00f6rbjuda|date=27 March 2020|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Swedish Constitution|Swedish constitution]] mandates that the relevant expert agency, in this case [[Public Health Agency of Sweden|the Public Health Agency]], must issue advice prior to any government actions aiming to prevent the spread of the virus with a strong mandate that the expert agencies should initiate actions, avoiding [[Ministerstyre|rule by ministers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gp.se/1.26081990|title=\"Vi epidemiologer har f\u00e5tt lite f\u00f6r stor makt\"|last=TT|date=2020-03-28|website=gp.se|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> The independece of Swedish agencies and the choice of 'recommendations' instead of legislation has received much coverage in international media.<ref name=\"samtalet8aprilsida4\">{{cite web |title=Samtalet om Sverige 1\u20137 april 2020 |url=https://si.se/app/uploads/2020/04/samtalet-om-sverige-1-7-april-1.pdf |website=www.si.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |page=4 |language=sv |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Swedish [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|foreign minister]], [[Ann Linde]] described Sweden as having \u2018rather small ministries, but rather big authorities\u2019 (with the Public Health Agency being one such authority), and this going back 300-400 years, and Sweden being characterized by a very high level of trust in its authorities from both the people and the politicians, and that Swedes had a very strong urge to following recommendations from authorities, thus making legislation largely unnecessary. When asked if Sweden would consider stronger restriction, L\u00f6fven and Linde has both made clear that the Swedish government wouldn't hesitate to do so if deemed necessary and on advice from the expert agencies, but that such measures needed to be taken at the right time, and that they believe it's hard do make people obey [[lockdown|lockdowns]] for an extended period.<ref name=\"lindecnn\">{{cite web |title=Ann Linde: \u201dFinns m\u00e5nga myter om svenska strategin\u201d |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/ann-linde-finns-manga-myter-om-svenska-strategin/ |website=www.expressen.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=9359b030-704e-11ea-aa9a-936e6c4209ee&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMy0yMi9zd2VkZW4tcHJpbWUtbWluaXN0ZXItc2F5cy1wcmVwYXJlLWZvci1tb3JlLXJlc3RyaWN0aXZlLXBvbGljaWVz|title=Sweden Prime Minister Says Prepare for More Restrictive Policies|last=Rolander|first=Niclas|date=22 March 2020|website=bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n\n[[File:FHM-Covid-19-Undvik-smitta-a4-engelska-raster.svg|thumb|upright=1.5|In response to COVID-19, the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] issued a series of infographics in different languages describing how to protect oneself and others from infection.]]<!--This image is specially made in response to COVID-19, and is general on purpose-->\n===Recommendations===\nOn 10 March, responding to indications of [[Transmission (medicine)#Definition and related terms|community transmission]], the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden|Public Health Agency]] advised everyone with respiratory infection, even mild ones, to refrain from social contacts where there is a risk of spreading the virus, in private as well as working life. They also ask health care staff working with risk groups, including nursing homes, not work if they have any symptoms of respiratory infection. Relatives of elderly should also avoid unnecessary visits at hospitals and in facilities for elderly, and never visit if there are any respiratory symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/flera-tecken-pa-samhallsspridning-av-covid-19-i-sverige/|title=Flera tecken p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llsspridning av covid-19 i Sverige \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stefansson |first1=Klara |title=Risken f\u00f6r coronaspridning i Sverige h\u00f6js till \"mycket h\u00f6g\" |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/risken-for-coronaspridning-i-sverige-hojs-till-mycket-hog |website=SVT Nyheter |language=sv |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 16 March, the agency of Sweden recommended that people over 70 should limit close contact with other people, and employers should recommend their employees work from home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/personer-over-70-bor-begransa-sociala-kontakter-tills-vidare/|title=Personer \u00f6ver 70 b\u00f6r begr\u00e4nsa sociala kontakter tills vidare \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se}}</ref> The following day, the agency recommended that secondary schools and universities use distance learning,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/larosaten-och-gymnasieskolor-uppmanas-nu-att-bedriva-distansundervisning/|title=L\u00e4ros\u00e4ten och gymnasieskolor uppmanas nu att bedriva distansundervisning \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se}}</ref> with schools following suit all over the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svd.se/presstraff-i-dag-med-utbildningsministern|title=L\u00f6fven: Gymnasier ska g\u00e5 \u00f6ver till distansstudier}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an analysis of mobile network data from the [[Easter|Easter week]] carried out by [[mobile network operator]] [[Telia]], most Swedes had followed the agency's recommendations to avoid unnecessary travels during the Easter holidays. Overall, travel from the Stockholm region had decreased by 80-90%, and the number of citizens of [[Stockholm]] travelling to popular holiday destinations like [[Gotland]] and the ski resorts in [[\u00c5re]] had fallen with more than 90%. Travel between other regions in Sweden had fallen as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stockholmare stannar hemma i p\u00e5sk |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/snabbkollen/stockholmare-stannar-hemma-i-pask |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Svenskarna stannar hemma under p\u00e5sklovet |url=http://press.telia.se/pressreleases/svenskarna-stannar-hemma-under-paasklovet-2990179 |website=Mynewsdesk |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref> [[Ferry|Ferry-line]] operator [[Destination Gotland]], who previously had called on their customers to rethink their planned trips for Easter, reported that 85% of all bookings had been rescheduled.<ref>{{cite web |last1=S. Zetterdahl |first1=Christian |title=85 procent har bokat av p\u00e5skresan med Gotlandsf\u00e4rjan |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/ost/85-procent-har-bokat-av-resan-med-gotlandsfarjan |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Rules and legislation===\nOn 11 March, the same day as the first Swedish death to COVID-19, the Swedish government passed a new law, limiting [[freedom of assembly]] by temporarily banning all gatherings larger than 500 people, with threat of fine and prison.<ref name=\":34\" /> The ban will apply until further notice.<ref name=\"Klart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gp.se/nyheter/sverige/klart-inga-evenemang-med-fler-%C3%A4n-500-bes%C3%B6kare-1.25224161|title=Klart: Inga evenemang med fler \u00e4n 500 bes\u00f6kare|date=11 March 2020|website=gp.se|language=sv|trans-title=Clear: No events with more than 500 visitors}}</ref>\nOn 27 March the government announced that gatherings of more than 50 people were banned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.krisinformation.se/nyheter/2020/mars/ytterligare-begransning-sammankomster|title=F\u00f6rbud mot allm\u00e4nna sammankomster med fler \u00e4n 50 personer|date=2020-03-27|access-date=2020-03-28|language=sv}}</ref><ref name=\"SVD50people\">{{cite web |url=https://www.svd.se/stefan-lofven-och-rikspolischefen-haller-presstraff/ |title=Sammankomster p\u00e5 \u00f6ver 50 personer f\u00f6rbjuds |first1=Hanna| last1=Frejdeman |date=27 March 2020 |website= |publisher=SvD |access-date=27 March 2020 |quote= |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nAgain, on the 11th of March, the karensdag, the unpaid first day of sick leave, was temporarily discontinued in an effort to encourage people to stay home if they were experiencing symptoms that are consistent with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20200311/sweden-changes-sick-pay-rules-to-help-fight-coronavirus|title=Sweden Changes Sick Pay Rules to Help Fight CoronaVirus|last=|first=|date=|website=thelocal.se|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 13 March, the government decided to temporarily abolish the demand of a doctor's certificate for 14 days for people staying home from work due to illness (i.e. sick pay period). Previously a doctor's certificate was needed after seven days.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Olsson|first=Jonas|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/regeringen-kravet-pa-lakarintyg-vid-sjukdom-avskaffas|title=Regeringen: Kravet p\u00e5 sjukintyg avskaffas tillf\u00e4lligt|date=13 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=13 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, the government introduced new restrictions to bars and restaurants requiring all service to be table service only. Restaurants were also recommended increase the space between the tables. Venues that do not adhere to the new restrictions could be shut down.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Larsson|first=Ylva|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nya-forbudet-endast-bordsservering-tillats-pa-restauranger-och-barer|title=Nya restriktioner: Endast bordsservering till\u00e5ts p\u00e5 restauranger och barer|date=2020-03-24|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nya-forbudet-endast-bordsservering-tillats-pa-restauranger-och-barer|title=Nya restriktioner: Endast bordsservering till\u00e5ts p\u00e5 restauranger och barer|date=24 March 2020|language=sv|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBeginning on 1 April, all private visits to nursing homes was outlawed by the government. Many [[Municipality (Sweden)|municipality]] had already forbidden such visits. The national ban was however general, and those in charge of the facilities would be able to make exceptions under special circumstances, provided that the risk of spread of the virus was low.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nationellt bes\u00f6ksf\u00f6rbud p\u00e5 \u00e4ldreboenden |url=https://www.lidkopingsnytt.nu/2020/03/31/nationellt-besoksforbud-pa-aldreboenden/ |website=Lidk\u00f6pingsnytt |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=31 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Travel restrictions===\nThe government has issued progressively stricter advisories against travel. Beginning on 17 February, the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Swedish Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] advised against all trips to [[Hubei Province]], [[China]], as well as non-essential travel to the rest of [[China]] apart from [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macao]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/kina---avradan/|title=Kina - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=26 January 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/ud-stramar-at-rekommendationerna-for-resor-till-kina/|title=UD stramar \u00e5t rekommendationerna f\u00f6r resor till Kina|date=2020-02-17|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\nOn 2 March the Ministry for Foreign Affairs advised against trips to [[Iran]], due to the uncontrolled spread of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Covid-19]] in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/iran---avradan/|title=Iran - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=27 February 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Swedish Transport Agency]] also revoked [[Iran Air]]'s permit for Iranian flights to land in Sweden from the same date.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Andersson|first=Jane|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/skane/inga-sarskilda-coronakontroller-pa-kastrup|title=Inga flyg med Iran Air till Kastrup|date=3 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=15 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/iran---avradan/|title=Iran - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=2020-02-27|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> According to the foreign ministry, there were several thousands Swedish citizens in Iran at the time of the ban, many of them with difficulties getting back to Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Param |first1=Babak |last2=Axelsson |first2=Staffan |title=Svenskar fast i Iran \u2013 \u201dIngen fr\u00e5n Sverige har s\u00f6kt mig\u201d |url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=7418320 |website=Sveriges Radio |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref> On 6 March, the Ministry for Foreign Affairs advised against all non-necessary trips to northern [[Italy]], specifically the regions of [[Piedmont|Piemonte]], [[Liguria]], [[Lombardy|Lombardia]], [[Emilia-Romagna]], [[Trentino-Alto Adige/S\u00fcdtirol|Trentino-Alto Adige]], [[Aosta Valley|Valle d'Aosta]], [[Veneto]], [[Friuli Venezia Giulia]], [[Marche]] and [[Tuscany|Toscana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/italien---avradan/|title=Italien - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=6 March 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref> [[Turin]], [[Milan]], [[Venice]], [[Verona]], [[Trieste]] and [[Florence]] are large cities in these regions. The [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]], who initiated the recommendation for the Ministry for Foreign Affairs, states that the decision is based solely on the strain of the Italian health care system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/folkhalsomyndigheten-har-rekommenderat-avradan-fran-resor-till-norra-italien/|title=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten har rekommenderat avr\u00e5dan fr\u00e5n resor till norra Italien \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten|website=folkhalsomyndigheten.se|language=sv|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> On similar grounds, the foreign affairs ministry also advised against all non-necessary travel to the city of [[Daegu]] and the province of [[North Gyeongsang Province|Gyeongbuk]] in [[South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/sydkorea---avradan/|title=Sydkorea - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=6 March 2020|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The advice regarding travels to Italy was extended 10 March to include all of its regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/uds-reseinformation/ud-avrader/italien---avradan/|title=Italien - avr\u00e5dan|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=2020-03-10|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Finally, all international travel was discouraged on 14 March. The advice was to be in place for one month, after which it would be up for review.<ref name=exceptionelltlage>{{cite web |last1=Karlsson |first1=Amanda |title=UD om strandade svenskarna: \"Exceptionellt l\u00e4ge\" |url=https://www.bohuslaningen.se/nyheter/v%C3%A4rlden/ud-om-strandade-svenskarna-exceptionellt-l%C3%A4ge-1.26027863 |website=bohuslaningen.se |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Makar|first=Maria|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/coronaviruset-ud-avrader-fran-icke-nodvandiga-resor-till-alla-lander|title=Coronaviruset \u2013 UD avr\u00e5der fr\u00e5n icke n\u00f6dv\u00e4ndiga resor till alla l\u00e4nder|date=2020-03-14|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref> Travel from non-[[European Union|EU]]/[[European Economic Area|EEA]] member states was stopped on 17 March<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.regeringen.se/artiklar/2020/03/fragor-och-svar--inresestopp-till-eu-via-sverige/|title=Fr\u00e5gor och svar \u2013 inresef\u00f6rbud till EU via Sverige|last=Regeringskansliet|first=Regeringen och|date=2020-03-17|website=Regeringskansliet|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> and unnecessary travel within Sweden was advised against on 19 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.krisinformation.se/nyheter/2020/mars/tank-over-om-resan-ar-nodvandig|title=Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten: T\u00e4nk \u00f6ver om resan verkligen \u00e4r n\u00f6dv\u00e4ndig|website=krisinformation.se|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/mars/tank-over-om-resan-verkligen-ar-nodvandig|title=T\u00e4nk \u00f6ver om resan verkligen \u00e4r n\u00f6dvandig|date=19 March 2020|language=sv|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe foreign ministry estimated that between 40,000 and 60,000 Swedes were stranded abroad in late March.<ref name=exceptionelltlage /><ref name=tiotusentalsstrandadesvenskar>{{cite web |author1=Emma Bouvin |author2=Karin Eriksson |title=Tiotusentals strandade svenskar v\u00e4djar om hj\u00e4lp att komma hem - DN.SE |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328103701/https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/tiotusentals-strandade-svenskar-vadjar-om-hjalp-att-komma-hem/ |website=web.archive.org |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April, the foreign ministry extended the advice against all non-essential travel abroad until 15 June, when it would again be reconsidered.<ref>{{cite web |title=Utlandsresor \u2013 f\u00f6rl\u00e4ngd avr\u00e5dan fr\u00e5n icke n\u00f6dv\u00e4ndiga resor till alla l\u00e4nder |url=https://www.regeringen.se/pressmeddelanden/2020/04/utlandsresor--forlangd-avradan-fran-icke-nodvandiga-resor-till-alla-lander |website=Regeringskansliet och Regeringskansliet |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=sv |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Economics===\nIn mid-March, the government proposed a 300 billion [[Swedish krona|SEK]] (\u20ac27bn) emergency package to reduce the economic impact of the crisis. The proposal included a system with a reduction in [[working time|work hours]] where the government will pay half to salary, aiming to help businesses stay afloat without having to do layoffs. Further, the government would pay the employer's expenses for any [[sick leave]]s, which is normally shared between the employer and the state.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liljestr\u00f6m |first1=Elias |url=https://www.thelocal.se/20200317/what-does-the-coronavirus-mean-for-swedish-economy |title=What does the coronavirus mean for the Swedish economy?|website=thelocal.se |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The normal costs of employer contributions have also been temporarily discontinued for small business owners. This will save small businesses approximately 5000 SEK per employee each month but will result in a loss of tax revenue of 33 billion SEK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/nytt-krispaket-presenteras-av-regeringen/|title=Tillf\u00e4lligt slopad arbetsgivaravgift i nytt krispaket|date=25 March 2020|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The budget emergency package proposed by the government in mid-March to lessen the economic impact of the crisis was supported across the political spectrum, including all parties in opposition in the [[Riksdag]]. It was also welcomed by [[trade union]]s as well as the private and business sectors. However, some union representatives stressed that 'it won't be enough', a view shared by the biggest [[employer's organisation]], the [[Confederation of Swedish Enterprise]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Larsson |first1=Thomas |title=Oppositionen sluter upp bakom regeringens st\u00f6dpaket |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/ekonomi/oppositionen-sluter-upp-bakom-regeringens-stodpaket |website=SVT Nyheter |language=sv |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLocal governments, such as the [[G\u00e4vle kommun|municipal government in G\u00e4vle]], have applied measures to businesses delaying the payment of invoices until September 1, 2020 at the earliest and deferring rent payments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gavle.se/service-och-information/information-om-coronaviruset/foretag-och-naringsliv-gallande-coronaviruset/|title=F\u00f6retag och n\u00e4ringsliv \u2013 coronaviruset|work=G\u00e4vle kommun|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\nOn 2 April, the [[Financial Supervisory Authority (Sweden)|Financial Supervisory Authority]] ('''Finansinspektionen''<nowiki/>') decided that Swedish banks temporarily can allow exemptions for housing mortgage lenders regarding amortizing of loans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fi.se/sv/publicerat/pressmeddelanden/2020/banker-far-ge-alla-bolanetagare-undantag-fran-amortering/|title=Banker f\u00e5r ge alla bol\u00e5netagare undantag fr\u00e5n amortering - Finansinspektionen|website=fi.se|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Response from the public healthcare system==\n\n===Testing===\nThe first tests were carried out in January, and according to the [[Swedish Public Health Agency]], \u2018around twenty tests\u2019 had already been carried out before the first positive case was confirmed on 30 January.<ref name=fhmpress200131 /> The agency considered that all individuals who developed any symptoms of disease in the respiratory tract after visiting [[Wuhan]] should be tested, even those with less severe symptoms.<ref name=\"annuingacoronafall\">{{cite web |last1=Cederberg |first1=Jesper |title=\u00c4nnu inga coronafall i Sverige |url=https://lakartidningen.se/Aktuellt/Nyheter/2020/01/Annu-inga-coronafall-i-Sverige/ |website=L\u00e4kartidningen |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv-SE |date=27 January 2020}}</ref> The Public Health Agency expanded testing for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|Covid-19]] on 4 March beyond only those who have been in risk areas abroad, to also test cases of pneumonia without known cause.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Thomsen|first=Dante|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nu-ska-fler-svenskar-testas-for-coronavirus|title=Nu ska fler svenskar testas f\u00f6r coronavirus|date=4 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=7 March 2020|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nInitially, all tests were carried out at the agency's [[Public Health Agency of Sweden#High-containment laboratory|high-containment laboratory]] in [[Solna]]. But in mid-February, in order to increase testing capacity and allow for faster test results, testing also began at the [[Medical laboratory|clinical medical laboratories]] in [[Sahlgrenska University Hospital|G\u00f6teborg]], [[Halmstad]], [[Sk\u00e5ne University Hospital|Lund]], [[Sk\u00f6vde]], [[Stockholm]], [[Norrland University Hospital|Ume\u00e5]] and [[University Hospital|Uppsala]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pramsten |first1=Sara |title=Fler labb f\u00e5r m\u00f6jlighet att analysera coronavirus |url=https://lakartidningen.se/Aktuellt/Nyheter/2020/02/Fler-labb-far-mojlighet-att-analysera-Coronavirus/# |website=L\u00e4kartidningen |publisher=L\u00e4kartidningen F\u00f6rlag AB |accessdate=12 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308211841/https://lakartidningen.se/Aktuellt/Nyheter/2020/02/Fler-labb-far-mojlighet-att-analysera-Coronavirus/ |archivedate=8 March 2020 |language=sv-SE |date=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nBetween 27 March and 3 April, the health agency tested approximately 800 randomly selected individuals in Stockholm County, to seek knowledge of the then current infection rate.<ref name=\"Resultat fr\u00e5n unders\u00f6kning av f\u00f6rek\">{{cite web |title=Resultat fr\u00e5n unders\u00f6kning av f\u00f6rekomsten av covid-19 i region Stockholm \u2014 Folkh\u00e4lsomyndigheten |url=https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2020/april/resultat-fran-undersokning-av-forekomsten-av-covid-19-i-region-stockholm/ |website=www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se |accessdate=9 April 2020 |language=sv |format=Press release |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \nAs it was estimated that Stockholm County by then had the highest infection rate in Sweden, the agency choose to focus on that region.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hansson |first1=Anna |title=Tester ska visa coronakurvan i Sverige |url=https://www.nyteknik.se/samhalle/tester-ska-visa-coronakurvan-i-sverige-6991681 |website=Ny Teknik |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=sv |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> According to the results, 2.5% of the local population were carrying the virus in the upper respiratory tract during the surveyed period.<ref name=\"Resultat fr\u00e5n unders\u00f6kning av f\u00f6rek\"/>\nBased on the study and a [[doubling time]] of 6-7 days, the agency concluded that 5-10% of the population in the region were carrying the virus on 9 April.<ref Name=mellan5och10 />\n\nAt the end of March, the number of tests carried out each week numbered 10.000.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bergendorff |first1=Johan |title=Tegnell: Mer testning skulle skydda \u00e4ldre b\u00e4ttre |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/vetenskap/tegnell-mer-testning-skulle-skydda-aldre-battre |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=sv |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Capacity===\nThe [[Stockholm International Fairs]], Stockholmsm\u00e4ssan, are being converted into a field hospital with the help of the [[Swedish Army|Swedish Defence Forces]]. The field hospital will be able to house 600 seriously and critically sick patients.<ref name=\"stockholmsmassan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/sthlm/har-byggs-stockholmsmassan-om-till-sjukhus/|title=H\u00e4r byggs Stockholmsm\u00e4ssan om till sjukhus|date=2020-03-27|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The Swedish Defence Forces will provide equipment for 30 of the 600 beds and the [[Stockholm Regional Council]] will provide the remaining 570.<ref name=\"stockholmsmassan\"/> The facilities are used for treating less severe cases, as opposed to those needing [[Intensive care unit|intensive care]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bj\u00f6rk |first1=Frida |title=\u00d6verl\u00e4kare sl\u00e5r larm om t\u00e4ltet p\u00e5 \u00d6stra: \u201dRiskerar m\u00e4nniskors liv\u201d |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/vast/overlakare-slar-larm-om-taltet-pa-ostra-riskerar-manniskors-liv |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:\u00d6stra Sjukhuset COVID-19 F\u00e4ltsjukhus.jpg|thumb|An army-constructed [[field hospital]] outside [[Sahlgrenska University Hospital|\u00d6stra Sjukhuset]] in [[Gothenburg]] on 23 March 2020. The tents contain temporary [[intensive care unit]]<nowiki/>s for COVID-19 patients. ]]\n[[File:Coronat\u00e4ltet .jpg|thumb|Medical tent set up outside [[Visby]] Hospital, 14 March 2020.]]\n[[File:Sahlgrenska_Corona_20200229_142008.jpg|thumb|Streetsigns outside Sahlgrenska hospital from late February telling those with potential symptoms of COVID-19 to wait outside the hospital.]]\nThe increasing number of cases in large areas such as Stockholm and Uppsala has resulted in the cancellation or postponement of up to 90% of planned surgeries, including cancer related surgeries.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carl\u00e9n|first=Linnea|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nara-halften-av-alla-planerade-operationer-installda|title=N\u00e4ra h\u00e4lften av alla planerade operationer inst\u00e4llda|date=2020-03-27|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|last2=Sima|first2=Lotta|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nBefore the pandemic, the Swedish healthcare system had the capacity to treat approximately 500 persons in [[Intensive Care Unit|intensive care units]] (ICU). The relatively low number of beds had stayed a source of concern as the crisis evolved, and even though the number had increased to 800 at the beginning of April, healthcare professionals continued to express worry that their hospitals would eventually run out of beds. According to the calculations of the Swedish health agency, up to 1300 ICU beds would be needed when Sweden reached the top of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olin |first1=Elisabet |title=Stor oro f\u00f6r kommande brist p\u00e5 intensivv\u00e5rdsplatser |url=https://lakartidningen.se/aktuellt/nyheter/2020/04/stor-oro-for-kommande-brist-pa-intensivvardsplatser/ |website=L\u00e4kartidningen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Grill |first1=Marja |last2=Sima |first2=Lotta |last3=Velizelos |first3=Aris |last4=Ulander |first4=Kenneth |title=IVA-platserna sinar i landet \u2013 stor os\u00e4kerhet om de kommer att r\u00e4cka |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/iva-platserna-sinar-i-landet-stor-osakerhet-om-platserna-kreported(cka |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=2002-04-13|language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> On 13 April, the [[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]] reported that the total number of ICU beds had risen to 1039, with an occupancy of 80%.<ref>{{cite web |title=20 nya d\u00f6dsfall i Sverige |url=https://www.nsk.se/2020/04/13/20-nya-dodsfall-i-sverige/ |website=Norra Sk\u00e5ne |accessdate=13 April 2020|language=sv-SE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Frejdeman |first1=Hannah |title=\u201dEfterrapportering att v\u00e4nta efter helgen\u201d |url=https://www.svd.se/just-nu-folkhalsomyndigheten-haller-presstraff |website=Svenska Dagbladet |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=sv |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Equipment===\nOn 13 March, media reported that there is a shortage in [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE) for health care staff, and hospitals in Stockholm have been forced to reuse disposable PPEs after sanitation. The regional Health Care Director warned about this scenario in early March and government agencies have temporarily waived the public procurement law in order to hastily procure more supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/coronaviruset/vardforraden-borjar-sina-engangsskydd-ateranvands/|title=Sjukhusens f\u00f6rr\u00e5d b\u00f6rjar sina \u2013 eng\u00e5ngsskydd \u00e5teranv\u00e4nds i Stockholm|website=expressen.se|language=sv|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The [[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]] ('''Socialstyrelsen''<nowiki/>') confirmed that there is no preparedness storage and nothing to distribute to the health care sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/tv/nyheter/coronaviruset/socialstyrelsen-det-finns-ingenting-att-distribuera/|title=Covid-19: Brist p\u00e5 skyddsutrustning och provtagningsmaterial|website=Expressen TV|language=sv|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/a/lA5mAo|title=Larmet inifr\u00e5n v\u00e5rden: \"Finns ingen skyddsutrustning\"|website=Aftonbladet|language=sv|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Staffing===\nOn 25 March 2020, Bj\u00f6rn Eriksson, the Director of Healthcare in Stockholm, appealed to anyone in the [[Stockholm Regional Council|Stockholm region]] who had experience in healthcare to volunteer. As of the 26 March 2020, 5100 people with healthcare experience had registered as volunteers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/sthlm/over-5000-har-anmalt-sig-for-att-forstarka-varden-i-stockholm/|title=\u00d6ver 5.000 har anm\u00e4lt sig f\u00f6r att f\u00f6rst\u00e4rka v\u00e5rden i Stockholm|date=27 March 2020|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe increasing number of cases in large areas such as Stockholm and Uppsala has resulted in the cancellation or postponement of up to 90% of planned surgeries, including cancer related surgeries.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carl\u00e9n|first=Linnea|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nara-halften-av-alla-planerade-operationer-installda|title=N\u00e4ra h\u00e4lften av alla planerade operationer inst\u00e4llda|date=2020-03-27|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|last2=Sima|first2=Lotta|language=sv}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on society==\n===Transport===\nOn 15 March, [[Scandinavian Airlines|SAS]] announced that they would temporarily reduce their workforce by 10,000 people which constitutes roughly 90% of their workforce.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sasgroup.net/newsroom/press-releases/2020/sas-pausar-merparten-av-verksamheten/ |title=SAS pausar merparten av verksamheten |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=15 March 2020 |website= |publisher=SAS |access-date=27 March 2020 |quote= |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nSoon almost every domestic flight were cancelled. Swedish authorities advised against all non-essential travel inside and out of Sweden. [[SAS Group|SAS]] decided to from 6 April 2020 fly only four domestic departures and four domestic arrivals from Arlanda, plus some international<ref>[https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/sas-fortsatter-trafikera-kiruna-och-lulea SAS beh\u00e5ller ett inrikesflyg \u2013 forts\u00e4tter trafikera fyra orter]</ref> while Norwegian cancelled all domestic flights in Sweden.<ref>[https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/norrbotten/norwegian-staller-in-alla-inrikesflyg Norwegian st\u00e4ller in alla inrikesflyg]</ref> Several airports closed altogether. Train routes were in general going with a more sparse schedule.\n\n===Education===\nOn 13 March 2020 the spring [[Swedish Scholastic Aptitude Test]] (''\u2032H\u00f6gskoleprovet\u2032''), was cancelled affecting approximately 70,000 prospective students who had registered themselves. This was the first time the Swedish Scholastic Aptitude Test has been cancelled since it was established in 1977.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Balcer Bednarska|first=Jaqueline|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/hogskoleprovet-3|title=H\u00f6gskoleprovet st\u00e4lls in \u2013 70 000 personer drabbas|date=2020-03-13|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref> On 23 March 2020 the [[National Agency for Education (Sweden)|Swedish National Agency for Education]] ('''Skolverket''<nowiki/>'), cancelled the [[Education in Sweden#National tests|national tests]] to give teachers in Sweden more time to prepare for the possibility of distance education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skolverket.se/om-oss/press/pressmeddelanden/pressmeddelanden/2020-03-23-varens-nationella-prov-stalls-in|title=[2020-03-23] V\u00e5rens nationella prov st\u00e4lls in|website=skolverket.se|language=sv|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Defence===\nThe [[Swedish Armed Forces]] cancelled the international [[military exercise]] Aurora 20 which was scheduled to be held between May and June. [[Austrian Armed Forces|Austria]] and [[Canadian Armed Forces|Canada]] had previously announced their cancellation of their planned participation.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Olsson |first1=Jonas |title=Milit\u00e4r\u00f6vningen Aurora skjuts upp |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/militarovningen-aurora-skjuts-upp |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=3 April 2020 |language=sv |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nOn 25 March, The [[Swedish Social Democratic Party]] together with the [[Swedish Trade Union Confederation]] decided to cancel their traditional [[May Day|May Day demonstrations]]. They will instead hold an event on a digital platform, which will include speeches by the Swedish prime minister and leader of the Social Democrats, [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]], as well as union confederation leader [[Karl-Petter Thorwaldsson]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yohannes |first1=Sofia |title=Socialdemokraternas 1 maj-t\u00e5g st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/socialdemokraternas-1-maj-tag-stalls-in |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Left Party (Sweden)]] also cancelled their nationwide demonstrations, and announced that there would instead be a digital celebration, including a speech by party leader [[Jonas Sj\u00f6stedt]].<ref>{{cite web |title=V\u00e4nsterpartiet anordnar digitalt f\u00f6rsta maj |url=https://www.etc.se/inrikes/vansterpartiet-anordnar-digitalt-forsta-maj |website=ETC |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Almedalen Week]], considered to be the biggest and most important forum in Sweden for seminars, debates and political speeches on current social issues, held in [[Visby]] every summer,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wendt|first1=Maria|title=Almedalen \u2013 ett nationalromantiskt spektakel|trans-title=The Almedalen Week \u2013 a spectacle in the spirit of national romanticism|url=http://www.svd.se/kultur/understrecket/almedalen-ett-nationalromantiskt-spektakel_3711736.svd|website=svd.se|publisher=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]|date=6 July 2014|language=Swedish|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> was cancelled as a result of the ban on large gatherings. The decision was taken on 1 April by the [[Gotland Municipality|organiser]] after consultation with the major political parties.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johansson |first1=Sara |title=Almedalsveckan 2020 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.dagensjuridik.se/nyheter/almedalsveckan-2020-stalls-in/ |website=Dagens Juridik |publisher=Blendow Publishing AB |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=sv-SE |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister Stefan L\u00f6fv\u00e9n had already announced that he had cancelled his planned participation in the upcoming event.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Larsson |first1=Carl |title=Statsministern avst\u00e5r Almedalen i sommar |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/ost/statsministern-avstar-almedalen-i-sommar |website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> A similar event in Stockholm, 'J\u00e4rvaveckan', was also cancelled, and won't be held until 2021.<ref>{{cite web |last1=R\u00e5gsj\u00f6 Thorell |first1=Andreas |title=J\u00e4rvaveckan flyttas fram till 2021 |url=https://www.resume.se/marknadsforing/sponsring-event/jarvaveckan-flyttas-fram-till-2021/ |website=www.resume.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Culture===\nOn 6 March, Swedish National Broadcaster [[SVT]] held a crisis meeting to consider broadcasting the live finals of [[Melodifestivalen 2020]] on 7 March without an audience, as a response to the growing outbreak. The Danish equivalent had recently decided to broadcast [[Dansk Melodi Grand Prix|their version]] of the finals without an audience. Ultimately, SVT decided to allow the audience to enter the arena, although they advised people who felt sick to stay at home.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Laurell|first=Agnes|url=https://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/danska-melodifestivalen-framfors-utan-publik/|title=SVT inf\u00f6r Melodifestivalen: Stanna hemma om du k\u00e4nner dig sjuk|date=6 March 2020|work=DN|access-date=8 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=Lenas|first2=Sverker|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nStarting 30 March 2020 the public library in G\u00e4vle will start with a book delivery service for people aged 70 or older. The library will also start a take-away service where you can pre-loan books and pick them in a take-away bag.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gavle.se/omsorg-och-stod/gavle-bibliotek-infor-take-away-bokkasse-for-alla-och-hemleverans-av-bocker-for-riskgruppe/|title=G\u00e4vle bibliotek inf\u00f6r Take away-bokkasse f\u00f6r alla och hemleverans av b\u00f6cker f\u00f6r riskgrupper|work=G\u00e4vle kommun|access-date=27 March 2020|language=sv-SE}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nIn [[Sport of athletics|athletics]], all [[2020 Diamond League]] events scheduled to be held in May were postponed, which included the meet in [[Stockholm]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Diamond League i Stockholm uppskjutet |url=https://www.svt.se/sport/friidrott/diamond-league-i-stockholm-uppskjutet |website=SVT Sport |accessdate=5 April 2020 |language=sv |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The world's largest [[half marathon]] in Gothenburg, [[G\u00f6teborgsvarvet]], was postponed until later in 2020 and then cancelled completely on 27 March.<ref>{{cite web|author=Publicerad |url=https://www.svd.se/goteborgsvarvet-helt-installt-i-ar |title=G\u00f6teborgsvarvet helt inst\u00e4llt i \u00e5r &#124; SvD |publisher=Svd.se |date= |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe annual recreational [[road bicycle racing|bicycle race]] [[V\u00e4tternrundan]], scheduled to be held in June, was also cancelled as a result of the pandemic. The organisers made the decision public on 2 April.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Holmqvist |first1=Tobias |title=V\u00e4tternrundan 2020 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/lokalt/ost/vatternrundan-2020-stalls-in|website=SVT Nyheter |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=2 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Klart: V\u00e4tternrundan inst\u00e4lld |url=https://www.dn.se/sport/klart-vatternrundan-installd/ |website=DN.SE |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=sv |date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, [[Swedish Football Association|the governing body for association football in Sweden]] formally announced that the premiere of the 2020 season for the first and second division leagues, men's [[Allsvenskan]] and [[Superettan]] as well as women's [[Damallsvenskan]] and [[Elitettan]], will be postponed to late May or early June. The decision will not affect the leagues below the second level.<ref>{{cite web |title=Klart: Allsvenskan skjuts upp |url=https://www.svt.se/sport/fotboll/klart-allsvenskan-stalls-in |website=SVT Sport |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Two days later it was announced that the 2020 edition of the association football award ceremony [[Fotbollsgalan]] was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Simon |first1=Bank |title=Sportbladet avsl\u00f6jar: Fotbollsgalan 2020 st\u00e4lls in |url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/sportbladet/fotboll/a/AdMegj/sportbladet-avslojar-fotbollsgalan-2020-stalls-in |website=Aftonbladet |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=sv |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Speedway]], the start of [[Elitserien (speedway)|Elitserien]], the highest league in [[Speedway in Sweden|the Swedish league system]], was rescheduled to 2 June. In order to manage a tighter schedule, the [[Sports governing body|sport's governing body]] Swedish Motorcycle and Snowmobile Federation also decided to cancel the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elitserien i speedway slopar kvartsfinalerna |url=https://ekuriren.se/sport/elitserien-i-speedway-slopar-kvartsfinalerna-sm5371664.aspx |website=ekuriren.se |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Debate==\nMany outside Sweden considered the Swedish policies and the measures taken by its [[Government of Sweden|government]] to fight the pandemic to be different when compared to most other countries. As a result, there was an increase in international news coverage of Sweden. Much of the coverage was neutral, but some of it also contained criticism.<ref name=\"samtalet8aprilsida5\">{{cite web |title=Samtalet om Sverige 1\u20137 april 2020 |url=https://si.se/app/uploads/2020/04/samtalet-om-sverige-1-7-april-1.pdf |website=www.si.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |page=5 |language=sv |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Many claimed the Sweden was pursuing a [[herd immunity|herd immunity strategy]], including [[President of the United States|US president]] [[Donald Trump]], who during a press briefing told the assembled media that Sweden was 'suffering very greatly' due to what he referred to as 'the herd', and that the US, if done the same, 'would have lost hundreds of thousands more people'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sweden says Trump criticism of coronavirus strategy 'factually wrong' |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/sweden-says-trump-criticism-of-coronavirus-strategy-factually-wrong |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en |date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/utrikes/trump-usa-hade-haft-tva-miljoner-doda-om-vi-foljt-sveriges-coronalinje |title=Trump: USA hade kanske haft tv\u00e5 miljoner d\u00f6da om vi f\u00f6ljt Sveriges coronalinje |publisher=SVT |author=Maria Makar|date=April 10, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020|lang=sv}}</ref> Responding partly to Trump's remarks, which she described by using the word \u2018misinformation\u2019, Swedish [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|foreign minister]] [[Ann Linde]] said that the \u2018so-called Swedish strategy\u2019 was one of many myths about Sweden, and described it as \u2018absolutely false\u2019. Linde said that the Swedish goal was no different from most other countries; to save lives, hinder the spread of the virus and make the situation manageable for [[Healthcare in Sweden|the health system]].<ref name=\"lindecnn\" /> Sweden's chief [[epidemiology|epidemiologist]] [[Anders Tegnell]], when asked about Trump's remarks, said that in his opinion Sweden was doing relatively well, and were no worse off than [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/tegnell-om-trumps-utspel-jamfort-med-new-york-fungerar-det-bra-i-sverige |title=Tegnell om Trumps utspel: Man ska inte ta det p\u00e5 allvar |publisher=SVT |author=Prescilia Haddad|date=April 8, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020|lang=sv}}</ref> Many news stories in international painted a picture of things being 'business as usual in Sweden, with its citizens ignoring the recommendations to practice [[social distancing]] and avoiding unnecessery travel.<ref name=\"samtalet8aprilsida5\" /> According to Linde, this is another of the myths about Sweden, and she claimed Sweden's combination of recommendations and legally binding measures had so far proven effective.<ref name=\"lindecnn\" />\n\nWith Sweden having taken some of the least strict measures of any European country or of countries with a similar number of cases, the response has been both criticised and praised by international media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=b63abe70-704c-11ea-ba39-7b28c7fe6635&url=L29waW5pb24vYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMy0yNy9jb3JvbmF2aXJ1cy13YW50LXRvLWVzY2FwZS1hLWxvY2tkb3duLXRyeS1zd2VkZW4/c3JuZD1wcmVtaXVtLWV1cm9wZQ==|title=Want to Escape a Lockdown? Try Sweden \u2014 Do you trust millions of your fellow citizens to do the right thing in a pandemic?|last=Laurent|first=Lionel|date=27 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=088c5a30-704d-11ea-a57a-3956084aed93&url=L25ld3MvYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAyMC0wMy0yMy9zd2VkZXMtdHJ5LWxhaXNzZXotZmFpcmUtbW9kZWwtaW4tY29udHJvdmVyc2lhbC12aXJ1cy1yZXNwb25zZQ==|title=Swedes Try Laissez-Faire Model in Controversial Virus Response|last=Rolander|first=Niclas|date=23 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/31de03b8-6dbc-11ea-89df-41bea055720b|title=Sweden bucks global trend with experimental virus strategy {{!}} Free to read|last=Milne|first=Richard|date=25 March 2020|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14th, a debate article was sent to Swedish newspapers signed by 22 academics, claiming that the strategy of the Swedish public health agency will lead to \"chaos in the healthcare system\". Moreover, they claimed that there is no transparency regarding the data used in the models made by the agency. [[Anders Tegnell]] from the public health agency responded to the criticism by saying that there is no lack in transparency in the agency's work and that all data is available to be downloaded by the public as an excel-file on their website. <ref>{{cite web |title=Ann Linde: \u201dForskare om Sveriges strategi: \u201dKommer att bli kaos\u201d\u201d |url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=7451820 |website=www.sverigesradio.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref>  Additionally Tegnell stated that the numbers of deaths presented in the published article are wrong, especially regarding the specific number of deaths per day. Another claim in the article saying that Sweden's statistics are closing in on to the ones of Italy was countered by Anders Tegnell saying that unlike Sweden, Italy and many other countries only report on deaths in hospitals, making it hard to compare the numbers of the different countries. <ref>{{cite web |title=\"Tegnells svar p\u00e5 skarpa kritiken i DN-debatt: Grundl\u00e4ggande felaktigheter\" |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/forskare-kritiska-til-fhm-lat-politikerna-ta-over |website=www.svt.se |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=sv}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Sweden medical cases}}\n {{clear}}\n\n===Additional data===\nAs of 27 March, nearly 3 out of 4 patients in intensive care in Sweden were men. The majority of them had underlying symptoms such as high blood pressure. Also, a disproportionately high number of deaths among males was reported.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Larsson|first=Ylva|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/nastan-8-av-10-av-de-svarast-sjuka-i-sverige-ar-man|title=N\u00e4stan 3 av 4 av de som intensivv\u00e5rdats i Sverige \u00e4r m\u00e4n|date=26 March 2020|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=27 March 2020|last2=Andersson|first2=Ki|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nAt a point, it was reported that a disproportionate number of those that had died by then were Swedish Somali (6)<ref name=\"Randhawa\">{{Cite news|last=Randhawa|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/lakarforening-larmar-over-halften-av-de-doda-ar-svensksomalier|title=L\u00e4karf\u00f6rening larmar: Flera svensksomalier bland coronad\u00f6dsfall i Stockholmsomr\u00e5det|date=2020-03-23|work=SVT Nyheter|access-date=2020-03-27|language=sv}}</ref>  out of 89<ref>{{cite web |title=30 mars: L\u00e4gesrapport om arbetet med det nya coronaviruset |url=https://www.sll.se/verksamhet/halsa-och-vard/nyheter-halsa-och-vard/2020/03/30-mars-lagesrapport-om-arbetet-med-det-nya-coronaviruset/ |website=Region Stockholm |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> deaths being members of the Swedish Somali community in the Stockholm region.<ref name=\"Randhawa\"/>\n\n====Charts====\nDatasource of the following charts are [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] official data compiled every day at noon,<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/> The numbers for individual dates may change as the daily data are normally adjusted when the figures get updated.\n\n<!-- Leave OFF THE LAST DAY as its only a small part of data and will give the charts a false shape -->\n<!-- Do NOT ONLY update the last day, this will invalidate the graphs! Update at least the last 14 days, as data is backdated by source -->\n{{Image frame|caption={{small|{{right|source: FOHM<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/>}}}}{{Center|'''Total confirmed cases'''}}|pos=top|align=left|border=no|content=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=720\n|linewidth=1\n|yGrid=|xGrid=\n|colors=#FF4500\n|xAxisAngle=-45\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|x=4 Feb, ., 26 Feb, 27 Feb, 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr\n|yAxisMin=0|yAxisMax=12000\n|yAxisTitle=Cases\n|y=1, 1, 2, 3, 11, 14, 14, 19, 32, 61, 86, 146, 179, 225, 326, 424, 620, 771, 923, 994, 1063, 1146, 1265, 1410, 1553, 1733, 1867, 1984, 2166, 2396, 2710, 2996, 3362, 3662, 3943, 4357, 4832, 5318, 5873, 6474, 6831, 7172, 7563, 8302, 8958, 9603, 10055, 10445, 10900, 11321, 11445\n}}}}\n\n<!-- Leave OFF THE LAST DAY as its only a small part of data and will give the charts a false shape -->\n<!-- Do NOT ONLY update the last day, this will invalidate the graphs! Update at least the last 14 days, as data is backdated by source -->\n{{Image frame|caption={{small|{{right|source: FOHM<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/>}}}}{{Center|'''Cases per day'''}}|pos=top|align=center|border=no|content=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=rect\n|width=720\n|showValues=offset:2\n|yGrid=|xGrid=\n|colors=#F46D43\n|xAxisAngle=-45\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|x=4 Feb, ., 26 Feb, 27 Feb, 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr, 3 Apr, 4 Apr, 5 Apr, 6 Apr, 7 Apr, 8 Apr, 9 Apr, 10 Apr, 11 Apr, 12 Apr, 13 Apr, 14 Apr\n|yAxisMin=0|yAxisMax=800\n|yAxisTitle=Cases\n|y=1, 0, 1, 1, 8, 3, 0, 5, 13, 29, 25, 60, 33, 46, 101, 98, 196, 151, 152, 71, 69, 83, 119, 145, 143, 180, 134, 117, 182, 230, 314, 286, 366, 300, 281, 414, 475, 486, 555, 601, 357, 341, 391, 739, 656, 645, 452, 390, 455, 421, 124\n}}}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n<!-- Leave OFF THE LAST DAY as its only a small part of data and will give the charts a false shape -->\n<!-- Do NOT ONLY update the last day, this will invalidate the graphs! Update at least the last 14 days, as data is backdated by source -->\n{{Image frame|caption={{small|{{right|source: FOHM<ref name=\"FHM_Official_stats\"/>}}}}{{Center|'''Total confirmed deaths'''}}|pos=top|align=left|border=no|content=\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=720\n|yGrid=|xGrid=\n|colors=#000000\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-45\n|x=4 Feb, ., 26 Feb, 27 Feb, 28 Feb, 29 Feb, 1 Mar, 2 Mar, 3 Mar, 4 Mar, 5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 